<h1>3.4.2 Aorist group</h1>
<p>Status: <em>draft</em></p>
<h2 id="relevant-postag-codes">Relevant postag codes:</h2>
<p><strong>Position and letters in postag string:</strong></p>
<ol type="1">
<li><p>part of speech: <strong>1st</strong>; letter: <strong>v</strong>
(verb)</p></li>
<li><p>person: <strong>2nd</strong>; numbers: <strong>1</strong>,
<strong>2</strong>, <strong>3</strong></p></li>
<li><p>number: <strong>3rd</strong>; letters: <strong>s</strong>
(singular), <strong>p</strong> (plural), <strong>d</strong>
(dual)</p></li>
<li><p>tense: <strong>4th</strong>; letters: <strong>p</strong>
(present), <strong>i</strong> (imperfect), <strong>r</strong> (perfect),
<strong>l</strong> (pluperfect), <strong>t</strong> (future perfect),
<strong>f</strong> (future), <strong>a</strong> (aorist)</p></li>
<li><p>mood: <strong>5th</strong>; letters: <strong>i</strong>
(indicative), <strong>s</strong> (subjunctive), <strong>o</strong>
(optative), <strong>n</strong> (infinitive), <strong>m</strong>
(imperative), <strong>p</strong> (participle)</p></li>
<li><p>voice: <strong>6th</strong>; letters: <strong>a</strong>
(active), <strong>p</strong> (passive), <strong>m</strong> (middle),
<strong>e</strong> (medio-passive)</p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Example postag string:</strong> v2saia— (verb, 2nd singular,
aorist, indicative, active)</p>
<h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
<p>Whereas the Greek imperfect denotes continued action in the past (I
was running) and the perfect a completed action in the past (I have run
(but I’m not running anymore), the aorist doesn’t take a stand on the
continuance or completion of an action, but simply expressess an
occurrence of it (I ran). (Note, that the tenses express time only in
the indicative mood.)</p>
<p>Smyth:</p>
<p>§1924. Ingressive Aorist.—The aorist of verbs whose present denotes a
state or a continued action, expresses the entrance into that state or
the beginning of that action. §1926. Resultative Aorist.—In contrast to
the imperfect (and present) the aorist denotes the result, end, or
effect of an action. §1927. Complexive Aorist.—The complexive aorist is
used to survey at a glance the course of a past action from beginning to
end.</p>
<p>Formation: - weak aorist - strong aorist - root aorist</p>
<h2 id="examples-of-aorist-tense-from-papygreek-corpus">Examples of
aorist tense from PapyGreek corpus</h2>
<ol type="1">
<li>[οὐ]κ ἔγρα[ψ]ας [φάσι]ν ὅτι <strong>αἴλαβα</strong> αὐτὰ εἲ οὐκ
<strong>αἴλαβα</strong>.<br>
(ouk égrapsas phásin hóti <strong>aílaba</strong> autà eì ouk
<strong>aílaba</strong>.)<br>
<em>…you have not sent me a message “I have received” or “I have not
received”.</em><br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/10359">o.claud.2.236</a>, 1-3 (sent.
1), transl. Bülow-Jacobsen (1997) p.&nbsp;59.</li>
</ol>
