<h2 id="discussion">Discussion</h2>
<p>first person sg -α / -ον (elaba jne.); note e.g.&nbsp;verb λέγω (légo) has
all these attested in Logeion/Morfo:</p>
<p>ἔειπον, εἶπα, εἶπά, εἶπον, ἔλεξα</p>
<p>so, when one papyrus editor has regularised ἶπα (îpa) to εἶπα (eîpa)
(bgu.1.15, 197 CE) and another εἶπα (eîpa) to εἶπον (eîpon) (sb.5.7574,
2nd BCE) and in many cases εἶπα is left unregularised, that’s just ok
(?), and we need to find ways to find these examples and see timelines
for preferences in the texts. Some of the earliest in upz (regularised
in 78 to -on (bc Jamie but according to edition apparatus(?)), but not
in 62…). The form εἶπον is more common than εἶπα (175 vs.&nbsp;35 hits in PN;
but NB due caution with numbers re apparatus entries, abbreviated words,
plural homonyms!)</p>